WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.125 --> 00:00:03.208
(light bright music)

2
00:00:08.040 --> 00:00:11.670
<v ->We are going to turn our attention to lower GI.</v>

3
00:00:11.670 --> 00:00:13.560
Nothing still to disclose.

4
00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:15.600
Here are our learning objectives

5
00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:18.690
and we're going to start with irritable bowel syndrome.

6
00:00:18.690 --> 00:00:21.630
Remember, this is a syndrome characterized

7
00:00:21.630 --> 00:00:25.320
by altered bowel habits and abdominal pain.

8
00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:28.955
The pain can get worse or better with bowel movements

9
00:00:28.955 --> 00:00:30.480
and there's an absence

10
00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:33.570
of detectable structural abnormalities.

11
00:00:33.570 --> 00:00:35.340
There are four subtypes.

12
00:00:35.340 --> 00:00:37.020
You will be leaving here today

13
00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:39.930
with a Bristol stool scale

14
00:00:39.930 --> 00:00:43.743
so that you can report tomorrow morning back on what the,

15
00:00:44.635 --> 00:00:47.280
(audiences laughing)

16
00:00:47.280 --> 00:00:48.483
You're awake.

17
00:00:50.520 --> 00:00:51.967
One of my patients one time told me,

18
00:00:51.967 --> 00:00:53.357
"You know why I like used to watch Dr. Weismiller

19
00:00:53.357 --> 00:00:55.890
'cause you're crazy like me."

20
00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:58.110
Okay, you can have constipation-predominant,

21
00:00:58.110 --> 00:00:59.760
diarrhea-predominant, a mixed,

22
00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:01.326
or it can be unsubtyped

23
00:01:01.326 --> 00:01:04.950
and it's based on the Bristol stool scale.

24
00:01:04.950 --> 00:01:09.780
Now here are the Rome IV diagnostic criteria for IBS.

25
00:01:09.780 --> 00:01:11.610
Average at least one day per week

26
00:01:11.610 --> 00:01:12.540
in the last three months,

27
00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:14.430
associated with two or more of the following.

28
00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:16.590
A pain related to defecation,

29
00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:17.730
associated with the change

30
00:01:17.730 --> 00:01:19.290
in the frequency of the stool,

31
00:01:19.290 --> 00:01:21.240
associated with the change in the form

32
00:01:21.240 --> 00:01:22.980
or the consistency.

33
00:01:22.980 --> 00:01:24.960
Now the pain related to defecation,

34
00:01:24.960 --> 00:01:25.800
it can get worse

35
00:01:25.800 --> 00:01:30.160
or can get better with the stooling.

36
00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:32.880
So I've got a history.

37
00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:34.980
We have to include psychosocial factors here.

38
00:01:34.980 --> 00:01:37.410
If I don't have any alarm symptoms or red flags

39
00:01:37.410 --> 00:01:39.750
and I meet the diagnostic criteria,

40
00:01:39.750 --> 00:01:42.540
we really don't need any further workup.

41
00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:46.050
If I'm considering that I do because of concern,

42
00:01:46.050 --> 00:01:47.220
then laboratory tests

43
00:01:47.220 --> 00:01:48.810
that may be helpful or listed there

44
00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:50.910
and I might need to do an imaging

45
00:01:50.910 --> 00:01:53.880
directly with colonoscopy or sigmoidoscopy.

46
00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:56.490
Now if we think about this therapy,

47
00:01:56.490 --> 00:01:59.730
it really is individualizing treatment.

48
00:01:59.730 --> 00:02:01.230
We want symptom relief

49
00:02:01.230 --> 00:02:04.050
and we want improvement in quality of life.

50
00:02:04.050 --> 00:02:05.100
They can be mild

51
00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:06.751
in which we're just using diet lifestyle.

52
00:02:06.751 --> 00:02:08.040
It could be moderate

53
00:02:08.040 --> 00:02:09.450
where I've gotta manage the stress

54
00:02:09.450 --> 00:02:11.130
that add pharmacotherapy

55
00:02:11.130 --> 00:02:14.732
or I can be have significant issues

56
00:02:14.732 --> 00:02:18.900
in terms of decreased functioning.

57
00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:22.230
Now patient symptoms are consistent

58
00:02:22.230 --> 00:02:23.550
with irritable bowel,

59
00:02:23.550 --> 00:02:25.440
history and physical as such.

60
00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:27.180
They don't have any red flags

61
00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:28.890
and those are the ones I'm thinking about.

62
00:02:28.890 --> 00:02:31.200
Unintentional and unexplained weight loss,

63
00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:33.780
rectal bleeding, a family history of bowel,

64
00:02:33.780 --> 00:02:36.480
ovarian cancer, a change in the bowel habits

65
00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:39.030
persisting more than six weeks

66
00:02:39.030 --> 00:02:41.913
in a person particularly who is maturing.

67
00:02:43.050 --> 00:02:46.350
Now if the patient does have any of these,

68
00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:47.716
I can confirm the diagnosis

69
00:02:47.716 --> 00:02:50.010
and I can proceed with treatment

70
00:02:50.010 --> 00:02:52.260
and it is symptom based as I said.

71
00:02:52.260 --> 00:02:53.913
Now look down there though.

72
00:02:54.870 --> 00:02:58.050
If you look at improving global symptoms

73
00:02:58.050 --> 00:03:00.321
with this functional disorder,

74
00:03:00.321 --> 00:03:02.880
using enteric coated peppermint oil

75
00:03:02.880 --> 00:03:05.370
has been shown to be globally

76
00:03:05.370 --> 00:03:07.950
helpful in terms of improvement.

77
00:03:07.950 --> 00:03:09.750
Now enteric-coated peppermint oil,

78
00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:12.420
you're using .2 to .4 CCs

79
00:03:12.420 --> 00:03:14.580
typically before each meal.

80
00:03:14.580 --> 00:03:15.870
It's gotta enteric-coated

81
00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:17.250
because as we learn with GERD,

82
00:03:17.250 --> 00:03:21.240
just taking in peppermint oil makes your GERD worse.

83
00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:23.250
Now I wanna go back to the upper GI

84
00:03:23.250 --> 00:03:24.918
and we had functional GI disorders.

85
00:03:24.918 --> 00:03:29.358
Remember 25% were organic, 75% were functional.

86
00:03:29.358 --> 00:03:31.140
From a practice perspective,

87
00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:33.600
if I diagnose you with something functional,

88
00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:36.243
everybody gets started on a trial of peppermint oil.

89
00:03:37.289 --> 00:03:38.190
Now if you're thinking,

90
00:03:38.190 --> 00:03:39.600
where am I gonna find enteric-coated,

91
00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:41.070
that's all you can find now

92
00:03:41.070 --> 00:03:44.160
because this is very, very popular.

93
00:03:44.160 --> 00:03:45.530
In my end of one studies,

94
00:03:45.530 --> 00:03:48.210
I would say 30 to 50% of the patients

95
00:03:48.210 --> 00:03:50.100
get much improvement.

96
00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:52.212
I had a woman about six years ago,

97
00:03:52.212 --> 00:03:53.460
she had been suffering

98
00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:56.460
from some form of functional disorder

99
00:03:56.460 --> 00:03:58.770
for at least 10 years.

100
00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:00.120
Never tried peppermint oil.

101
00:04:00.120 --> 00:04:00.953
Tried her on it,

102
00:04:00.953 --> 00:04:03.000
she had a 90% improvement.

103
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:04.650
She's like, "I cannot believe you.

104
00:04:04.650 --> 00:04:06.300
You like worked a miracle."

105
00:04:06.300 --> 00:04:08.602
Like, oh yeah, that's what I'm good at, miracles, yeah.

106
00:04:08.602 --> 00:04:10.500
That was just luck of the draw.

107
00:04:10.500 --> 00:04:12.600
But if they have diarrhea,

108
00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:14.370
typically we're using an antidiarrhea,

109
00:04:14.370 --> 00:04:17.033
bloating and distension probiotics

110
00:04:17.033 --> 00:04:20.280
or linaclotide or lubiprostone.

111
00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:22.380
Now antibiotics can be used here.

112
00:04:22.380 --> 00:04:23.213
It's interesting,

113
00:04:23.213 --> 00:04:25.350
even though there's not a infectious cause,

114
00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:28.860
rifaximin and neomycin have been shown to be helpful.

115
00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:31.061
Constipation, of course, soluble fiber

116
00:04:31.061 --> 00:04:33.453
is typically what we're reaching for.

117
00:04:34.380 --> 00:04:37.140
And then if there's a lot of abdominal pain and discomfort,

118
00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:41.190
antispasmodics, antidepressants can be helpful here.

119
00:04:41.190 --> 00:04:44.010
Now in terms of that fiber issue,

120
00:04:44.010 --> 00:04:46.440
what are the water soluble ones we're looking for?

121
00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:49.050
Well, we're trying to get a bulk laxative.

122
00:04:49.050 --> 00:04:52.170
If we're thinking about this in terms of diet,

123
00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:53.743
oats, apples, pear,

124
00:04:53.743 --> 00:04:58.743
we want all the skins on there, beans, legumes,

125
00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:01.023
these are low fermentability.

126
00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:04.620
And the way this helps is that it's secondary

127
00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:08.310
to increasing the fecal size bulk, okay?

128
00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:10.470
So this can be very helpful.

129
00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:11.820
Bulk is retained in the colon

130
00:05:11.820 --> 00:05:13.590
despite the microflora

131
00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:16.440
as psyllium is poorly fermented.

132
00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:19.950
So if we're using a water-soluble fiber like Citrucel,

133
00:05:19.950 --> 00:05:21.900
of course that's gonna be psyllium

134
00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:24.390
and this can be very helpful.

135
00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:26.250
Now water insoluble,

136
00:05:26.250 --> 00:05:30.120
whole wheat, whole bran, brown rice,

137
00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:32.580
all that fun stuff.

138
00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:34.680
It prevents constipation.

139
00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:36.930
It's indigestible.

140
00:05:36.930 --> 00:05:38.860
Its presence also speeds things up

141
00:05:38.860 --> 00:05:40.530
and moves things along

142
00:05:40.530 --> 00:05:44.730
so you can help prevent the GI blockage and constipation.

143
00:05:44.730 --> 00:05:46.650
So depending on what the issue is,

144
00:05:46.650 --> 00:05:49.830
you'll choose either water soluble or water insoluble.

145
00:05:49.830 --> 00:05:53.160
Now FODMAPs, okay.

146
00:05:53.160 --> 00:05:57.120
These may cause digestive discomfort in some patients.

147
00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.310
So restricting them has been shown

148
00:05:59.310 --> 00:06:03.750
to potentially be help to improve adults with IBS

149
00:06:03.750 --> 00:06:06.570
and any other functional GI disorder.

150
00:06:06.570 --> 00:06:09.150
So this is the second thing we have a discussion about

151
00:06:09.150 --> 00:06:11.280
when there's a functional GI disorder

152
00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:14.761
is how can I restrict my FODMAPs, okay?

153
00:06:14.761 --> 00:06:17.883
They're present in anything that's gluten containing,

154
00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:20.700
and therefore this may be the issue

155
00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:24.690
in patients who have non-celiac gluten sensitivity.

156
00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:28.616
You know, gluten-free is quite in right now.

157
00:06:28.616 --> 00:06:32.597
And this may be the issue in terms of why some patients

158
00:06:32.597 --> 00:06:35.970
with the non-celiac gluten sensitivity

159
00:06:35.970 --> 00:06:38.970
do better when they restrict gluten.

160
00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:41.463
They do not cause intestinal inflammation.

161
00:06:42.818 --> 00:06:44.520
Okay, so IBS then,

162
00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:47.430
self-help patient education, CBT.

163
00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:49.860
Global symptoms are improved with soluble

164
00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:52.080
but not insoluble fiber here.

165
00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:53.620
Lubiprostone and linaclotide

166
00:06:53.620 --> 00:06:57.270
are effective for constipation-predominant.

167
00:06:57.270 --> 00:06:59.280
Antispasmodics can be helpful,

168
00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.263
antidepressants helpful,

169
00:07:02.263 --> 00:07:04.563
and a diarrhea agents helpful.

170
00:07:06.113 --> 00:07:08.640
Okay, now psychological treatment.

171
00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:11.190
Look at the number needed to treat here, four.

172
00:07:11.190 --> 00:07:13.590
Hypnotherapy, CBT, and psychotherapy.

173
00:07:13.590 --> 00:07:15.750
Choose the one you'd like.

174
00:07:15.750 --> 00:07:17.520
Okay, but I have to treat four people

175
00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:20.283
to have one benefit from just this treatment.

176
00:07:21.540 --> 00:07:22.560
Here's the AGA.

177
00:07:22.560 --> 00:07:24.843
For a patient with functional abdominal pain,

178
00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:27.260
they meet the criteria Rome IV.

179
00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:30.732
Let's say you had to do a diagnostic evaluation

180
00:07:30.732 --> 00:07:34.560
with a colonoscopy and/or screening CT

181
00:07:34.560 --> 00:07:36.660
or a diagnostic CT.

182
00:07:36.660 --> 00:07:38.520
Unless there is a major change,

183
00:07:38.520 --> 00:07:40.293
you do not repeat the study.

184
00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:44.463
Okay, here's our AES question.

185
00:07:46.110 --> 00:07:48.120
19-year-old presents to your office for follow-up.

186
00:07:48.120 --> 00:07:49.911
She reports continued intermittent

187
00:07:49.911 --> 00:07:53.940
abdominal cramping and bloating, diarrhea, fatigue,

188
00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:55.443
4.5-kilo weight loss.

189
00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:59.640
She was diagnosed with IBS, you think it's celiac.

190
00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:00.840
Which one of the following should be used

191
00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:03.090
to establish a diagnosis?

192
00:08:03.090 --> 00:08:04.712
Colonoscopy; serologic testing;

193
00:08:04.712 --> 00:08:06.210
do serologic testing,

194
00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:08.250
and then what the heck get an endoscopy;

195
00:08:08.250 --> 00:08:09.720
and serologic testing initially,

196
00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:11.283
followed by a colonoscopy.

197
00:08:16.500 --> 00:08:19.847
Okay, C is the correct answer.

198
00:08:22.437 --> 00:08:25.290
We wanna do a screening test

199
00:08:25.290 --> 00:08:28.380
followed by a diagnostic test.

200
00:08:28.380 --> 00:08:31.669
This is preparing you for tomorrow morning at 8:00.

201
00:08:31.669 --> 00:08:33.240
There's gonna be so much fun.

202
00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:35.400
We're gonna talk about screening,

203
00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:37.830
sensitivity, specificity,

204
00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:39.717
positive, predictive value, negative.

205
00:08:39.717 --> 00:08:42.750
I mean you will be salivating it, so exciting.

206
00:08:42.750 --> 00:08:46.500
Okay, serologic testing and then an endoscopy.

207
00:08:46.500 --> 00:08:50.820
Okay, so celiac disease, this is autoimmune.

208
00:08:50.820 --> 00:08:53.490
If we look visually,

209
00:08:53.490 --> 00:08:55.500
you will see this kind of cracked-mud appearance

210
00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:57.000
to the mucosa.

211
00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:58.500
And when you do a biopsy

212
00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:03.450
and what we do is the proximal area of the small intestine.

213
00:09:03.450 --> 00:09:04.830
The second aspect of it,

214
00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:07.110
you see this blunting of the villi.

215
00:09:07.110 --> 00:09:08.850
Now you want to be tested

216
00:09:08.850 --> 00:09:12.183
when you're consuming a diet of gluten.

217
00:09:13.950 --> 00:09:15.000
Signs and symptoms,

218
00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.460
there's really not a typical presentation.

219
00:09:17.460 --> 00:09:19.470
And on the laboratory standpoint,

220
00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:21.660
you can see iron-deficiency anemia,

221
00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:25.380
folate deficiency, and vitamin D deficiency.

222
00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:26.850
Now how do we diagnose it?

223
00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:29.310
There are several serologic tests.

224
00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:32.045
If they say you have to choose two on the exam,

225
00:09:32.045 --> 00:09:33.573
you want to use the IgA

226
00:09:33.573 --> 00:09:36.480
anti-tissue transglutaminase antibody,

227
00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:38.820
and the endomysial antibody.

228
00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:40.710
If you only get one,

229
00:09:40.710 --> 00:09:44.883
then the IgA is the first line for serologic testing.

230
00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:48.180
You then do an assessment

231
00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:51.000
if that is positive of the distal aspect

232
00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.550
of the duodenum using an EGD,

233
00:09:53.550 --> 00:09:55.713
and you will see this villas flattening.

234
00:09:57.750 --> 00:09:59.310
How do we treat this?

235
00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:00.300
Gluten avoidance.

236
00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:01.440
Now what we don't know

237
00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:03.420
is what's the threshold of gluten

238
00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:05.940
And any individual can tolerate.

239
00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:07.560
Meaning, well, you know today,

240
00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:10.560
if you say I want to have a gluten-free meal out,

241
00:10:10.560 --> 00:10:12.240
they'll ask, is this an allergy

242
00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:14.400
or is this a preference?

243
00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:15.840
Because an allergy, you know,

244
00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:17.430
these are patients who have celiac disease.

245
00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:19.994
The other is maybe I just am sensitive to gluten,

246
00:10:19.994 --> 00:10:22.983
but I don't have defined celiac disease.

247
00:10:24.630 --> 00:10:27.480
Now inflammatory bowel disease.

248
00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:30.240
Onset here is usually young adults.

249
00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:32.583
More common among Caucasians.

250
00:10:33.420 --> 00:10:34.980
The spectrum is from anywhere,

251
00:10:34.980 --> 00:10:38.130
from Crohn's to ulcerative colitis.

252
00:10:38.130 --> 00:10:39.870
We know there's a genetic role.

253
00:10:39.870 --> 00:10:41.790
We don't have an infectious agent

254
00:10:41.790 --> 00:10:43.290
that's been identified.

255
00:10:43.290 --> 00:10:44.790
We know that there's tissue injury,

256
00:10:44.790 --> 00:10:46.830
so we assume that there must be some type

257
00:10:46.830 --> 00:10:50.040
of immune role as a mediator.

258
00:10:50.040 --> 00:10:52.343
And we know that there are serologic markers

259
00:10:52.343 --> 00:10:54.180
that help us differentiate

260
00:10:54.180 --> 00:10:57.240
between ulcerative colitis and Crohn's.

261
00:10:57.240 --> 00:10:59.010
Now if I'm trying to differentiate

262
00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:02.400
between inflammatory bowel disease and IBS,

263
00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:03.880
I can use fecal lactoferrin

264
00:11:03.880 --> 00:11:05.530
and calprotectin levels.

265
00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:09.420
These are serologic markers of bowel inflammation,

266
00:11:09.420 --> 00:11:10.860
which you should not be seeing

267
00:11:10.860 --> 00:11:13.530
with irritable bowel syndrome.

268
00:11:13.530 --> 00:11:17.130
This can be of help in differentiating the two.

269
00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:19.680
Now let's take a look at ulcerative colitis first.

270
00:11:19.680 --> 00:11:22.140
Remember, it's confined to the mucosa.

271
00:11:22.140 --> 00:11:23.250
It starts in the rectum

272
